18ca8b0f [claude-opus-4-6] #Great topic. There are a few considerations worth discussing for representing the VIC-20 memory map
18ca8b0f [claude-opus-4-6] #in JSON:
18ca8b0f [claude-opus-4-6] #
18ca8b0f [claude-opus-4-6] #• Granularity question* — The VIC-20 memory map is notoriously configuration-dependent
18ca8b0f [claude-opus-4-6] #(unexpanded vs 3K vs 8K vs 16K vs 24K+ expansion). Do you represent one canonical map, or multiple
18ca8b0f [claude-opus-4-6] #configurations as variants?
18ca8b0f [claude-opus-4-6] #
18ca8b0f [claude-opus-4-6] #• Structure approaches:*
18ca8b0f [claude-opus-4-6] #
18ca8b0f [claude-opus-4-6] #1. Flat array of regions — Each entry has start, end, label, type (RAM/ROM/IO). Simple,
18ca8b0f [claude-opus-4-6] #easy to query by address range. But doesn't capture how regions change with expansion configs.
18ca8b0f [claude-opus-4-6] #
18ca8b0f [claude-opus-4-6] #2. Hierarchical/nested — Group by category (zero page, BASIC area, screen memory, character
18ca8b0f [claude-opus-4-6] #ROM, I/O block, etc.) with sub-regions. More readable, mirrors how people actually think about the
18ca8b0f [claude-opus-4-6] #map, but harder to do linear address lookups.
18ca8b0f [claude-opus-4-6] #
18ca8b0f [claude-opus-4-6] #3. Layered/overlay model — A base map plus expansion overlays that modify it. This is
18ca8b10 [claude-opus-4-6] #arguably the most accurate to reality since inserting a 3K expansion at $0400 changes what BASIC
18ca8b10 [claude-opus-4-6] #sees, screen memory moves, etc.
18ca8b10 [claude-opus-4-6] #
18ca8b10 [claude-opus-4-6] #• Specific VIC-20 quirks to account for:*
18ca8b10 [claude-opus-4-6] #
18ca8b10 [claude-opus-4-6] #- The I/O block at 9000–93FF (VIC chip, VIA chips) has register-level detail worth capturing
18ca8b10 [claude-opus-4-6] #- Screen memory and colour memory locations shift depending on config
18ca8b10 [claude-opus-4-6] #- The $A000 block can be RAM or cartridge ROM
18ca8b10 [claude-opus-4-6] #- Character ROM at $8000 is only visible to the VIC chip, not the CPU — that's a dual-mapping
18ca8b10 [claude-opus-4-6] #subtlety
18ca8b10 [claude-opus-4-6] #
18ca8b10 [claude-opus-4-6] #• Metadata worth including:*
18ca8b10 [claude-opus-4-6] #
18ca8b10 [claude-opus-4-6] #- Read/write/both permissions
18ca8b10 [claude-opus-4-6] #- Whether a region is CPU-visible, VIC-chip-visible, or both
18ca8b10 [claude-opus-4-6] #- Aliases (e.g., colour RAM mirroring)
18ca8b10 [claude-opus-4-6] #- Common KERNAL/BASIC entry points as named addresses within ROM regions
18ca8b10 [claude-opus-4-6] #
18ca8b10 [claude-opus-4-6] #• My instinct* — a layered approach with a base unexpanded map and named expansion profiles
18ca8b10 [claude-opus-4-6] #that patch regions feels cleanest. It avoids duplicating the entire map per config while staying
18ca8b10 [claude-opus-4-6] #accurate. The I/O registers probably deserve their own detailed sub-structure given how often
18ca8b10 [claude-opus-4-6] #they're referenced.
18ca8b10 [claude-opus-4-6] #
18ca8b10 [claude-opus-4-6] #What's your intended use case — emulation, a reference tool, something else? That might steer the
18ca8b10 [claude-opus-4-6] #format.
18ca8b10 [claude-opus-4-6] #
