18ca8cc0 [claude-opus-4-6] #That's a solid starting point — flat, simple, easy to parse. A few thoughts:
18ca8cc0 [claude-opus-4-6] #
18ca8cc0 [claude-opus-4-6] #• What works well:*
18ca8cc0 [claude-opus-4-6] #- Having both hex and decimal address is convenient for different consumers
18ca8cc0 [claude-opus-4-6] #- Length is essential since VIC-20 regions vary from single bytes to multi-KB blocks
18ca8cc0 [claude-opus-4-6] #- Flat array means straightforward address lookups
18ca8cc0 [claude-opus-4-6] #
18ca8cc0 [claude-opus-4-6] #• Potential concerns:*
18ca8cc0 [claude-opus-4-6] #
18ca8cc0 [claude-opus-4-6] #• Redundancy* — hex and address represent the same value. You could derive one from the
18ca8cc0 [claude-opus-4-6] #other and keep the JSON leaner. Though I understand the convenience argument, especially if this is
18ca8cc0 [claude-opus-4-6] #also a human-readable reference.
18ca8cc0 [claude-opus-4-6] #
18ca8cc0 [claude-opus-4-6] #• Length ambiguity at this granularity* — Your example maps individual zero page locations
18ca8cc0 [claude-opus-4-6] #(length 1, length 2). Are you planning to do that for the entire 64K space? Zero page and the I/O
18ca8cc0 [claude-opus-4-6] #registers warrant byte-level detail, but the BASIC ROM from C000–DFFF probably doesn't need 8192
18ca8cc0 [claude-opus-4-6] #individual entries. You might end up with a mix of granularities, which is fine but worth being
18ca8cc0 [claude-opus-4-6] #intentional about.
18ca8cc0 [claude-opus-4-6] #
18ca8cc0 [claude-opus-4-6] #• Missing fields you might want later:*
18ca8cc0 [claude-opus-4-6] #- Read/write/both
18ca8cc0 [claude-opus-4-6] #- Category or type tag (zeropage, io, ram, rom, kernal, basic) for filtering
18ca8cc0 [claude-opus-4-6] #- Which expansion configs the entry applies to — that USR vector is always there, but other regions
18ca8cc0 [claude-opus-4-6] #shift
18ca8cc0 [claude-opus-4-6] #
18ca8cc0 [claude-opus-4-6] #• Naming* — "about" is a bit vague. Something like "label" or "description" might be
18ca8cc0 [claude-opus-4-6] #clearer, or even split into a short label and a longer description.
18ca8cc0 [claude-opus-4-6] #
18ca8cc0 [claude-opus-4-6] #• The big question* remains whether entries that change with expansion configs get separate
18ca8cc0 [claude-opus-4-6] #records, a config flag, or are handled some other way. At the zero page level it's less of an issue
18ca8cc0 [claude-opus-4-6] #since those locations are mostly stable across configs.
18ca8cc0 [claude-opus-4-6] #
18ca8cc0 [claude-opus-4-6] #Are you sourcing this from a specific reference like the Mapping the VIC or the Programmer's
18ca8cc0 [claude-opus-4-6] #Reference Guide?
18ca8cc0 [claude-opus-4-6] #
18ca8cc0 [roha]  ꔀ Fountain 1.7.2 ⛲  claude-opus-4-6 A\ 🪠 0.7° $0.014 2.962KB 12.83s
