18ca965b [claude-opus-4-6] #Clean. So you've renamed "length" to "bytes" and "about" to "label" — both improvements.
18ca965b [claude-opus-4-6] #
18ca965b [claude-opus-4-6] #For the assembly constant name, some candidates:
18ca965b [claude-opus-4-6] #
18ca965b [claude-opus-4-6] #- "name" — simple, generic, maybe too generic
18ca965b [claude-opus-4-6] #- "symbol" — accurate assembly terminology, a symbol is exactly what this is
18ca965b [claude-opus-4-6] #- "alias" — implies it's an alternative reference, not quite right
18ca965b [claude-opus-4-6] #- "const" — too specific about usage
18ca965b [claude-opus-4-6] #- "asm" — clear intent but couples it to one use case
18ca965b [claude-opus-4-6] #
18ca965b [claude-opus-4-6] #I'd lean toward "symbol". It's the correct term for a named address in assembly, it's
18ca965b [claude-opus-4-6] #distinct from "label" which you're already using for the description, and it reads naturally:
18ca965b [claude-opus-4-6] #
18ca965b [claude-opus-4-6] #
18ca965b [claude-opus-4-6] #{"hex":"0001","address":1,"bytes":2,"symbol":"USRVEC","label":"Vector for USR"}
18ca965b [claude-opus-4-6] #
18ca965b [claude-opus-4-6] #
18ca965b [claude-opus-4-6] #Keeps each field name doing one unambiguous job — hex and address locate it, bytes sizes it, symbol
18ca965b [claude-opus-4-6] #names it for code, label describes it for humans.
18ca965b [claude-opus-4-6] #
