18cacc3e [nitro@ryzen5] the 24 bytes for the CHRGET routine are interesting
18caccfe [claude-opus-4-6] #Yes, CHRGET is fascinating. It's one of the cleverest things in the Commodore ROM design.
18caccfe [claude-opus-4-6] #
18caccfe [claude-opus-4-6] #They copy a small machine language subroutine into zero page at boot so it runs faster — zero page
18caccfe [claude-opus-4-6] #addressing saves a cycle per instruction on the 6502. Since CHRGET is called constantly during
18caccfe [claude-opus-4-6] #BASIC parsing, those saved cycles add up significantly.
18caccfe [claude-opus-4-6] #
18caccff [claude-opus-4-6] #The really clever bit is that the BASIC text pointer at 7A-7B lives inside the subroutine
18caccff [claude-opus-4-6] #as the operand of a LDA instruction. So when CHRGET increments the pointer, it's literally
18caccff [claude-opus-4-6] #self-modifying code — it changes its own operand. This only works because it's in RAM, which is
18caccff [claude-opus-4-6] #another reason it has to be copied out of ROM.
18caccff [claude-opus-4-6] #
18caccff [claude-opus-4-6] #Some well-known tricks exploit this:
18caccff [claude-opus-4-6] #
18caccff [claude-opus-4-6] #- Wedge programs hook into CHRGET to intercept BASIC parsing, adding new commands. The DOS wedge
18caccff [claude-opus-4-6] #for disk drives is the classic example.
18caccff [claude-opus-4-6] #- You can watch 7A-7B to see where BASIC is currently reading from.
18caccff [claude-opus-4-6] #- Some copy protection schemes modify CHRGET to interfere with LIST or tamper detection.
18caccff [claude-opus-4-6] #
18caccff [claude-opus-4-6] #It's also worth noting that your earlier entry had it at 138 bytes which seems too large — the
18caccff [claude-opus-4-6] #actual CHRGET routine is more like 24-26 bytes. The reference manual may be grouping a larger
18caccff [claude-opus-4-6] #region there. Worth double-checking that boundary against your copy.
18caccff [claude-opus-4-6] #
18caccff [roha]  ꔀ Fountain 1.7.2 ⛲  claude-opus-4-6 A\ 🪠 0.7° $0.043 28.19KB 11.53s
