1a790b1a [gemini-3.1-pro] #clock, this generates a stripe frequency of exactly 6.0 MHz. Modern digital TVs typically sample
1a790b1b [gemini-3.1-pro] #standard-definition composite video at 13.5 MHz. Sampling a 6.0 MHz signal at 13.5 MHz gives
1a790b1b [gemini-3.1-pro] #exactly 2.25 samples per stripe. Because this isn't an integer, the TV's analog-to-digital
1a790b1b [gemini-3.1-pro] #converter samples different parts of the square wave (peak, rising edge, falling edge) on
1a790b1b [gemini-3.1-pro] #consecutive stripes. A 2.25 ratio creates an interference beat that perfectly explains your
1a790b1c [gemini-3.1-pro] #repeating "one dark, two bright" pattern.
