1a871aab [nitro@ryzen5] i am also curious about hdmi version, can i do audio and 576p over hdmi without running into regulatory hurdles?
1a871b8e [claude-opus-4-6] #The HDMI spec itself is licensed by HDMI Licensing Administrator. Using the HDMI name/logo or
1a871b8e [claude-opus-4-6] #claiming HDMI compliance on a product requires a license and fees. That's the regulatory hurdle.
1a871b8f [claude-opus-4-6] #
1a871b8f [claude-opus-4-6] #However, the electrical signalling (TMDS over 4 differential pairs) is essentially the same as DVI,
1a871b8f [claude-opus-4-6] #which has no such licensing requirement. Many hobbyist and open source projects output DVI-D
1a871b8f [claude-opus-4-6] #signals over an HDMI connector without calling it HDMI. TVs accept it fine.
1a871b90 [claude-opus-4-6] #
1a871b90 [claude-opus-4-6] #DVI-D doesn't carry audio though. Audio over TMDS is specifically an HDMI feature, covered by the
1a871b90 [claude-opus-4-6] #HDMI spec.
1a871b90 [claude-opus-4-6] #
1a871b91 [claude-opus-4-6] #For a personal/hobby project none of this matters practically - no one is policing your bench. If
1a871b91 [claude-opus-4-6] #you're selling a product, you'd want to either:
1a871b91 [claude-opus-4-6] #
1a871b91 [claude-opus-4-6] #- License HDMI (expensive, annual fees)
1a871b92 [claude-opus-4-6] #- Call it DVI-compatible and skip audio
1a871b92 [claude-opus-4-6] #- Use a different audio path (I2S DAC, 3.5mm jack)
1a871b92 [claude-opus-4-6] #
1a871b92 [claude-opus-4-6] #On the RP2350 side, Pico2 doesn't have the PIO clock speed for raw TMDS bit-banging the way RP2040
1a871b93 [claude-opus-4-6] #projects (like PicoDVI) managed at 252MHz+. You'd likely need an HDMI serialiser chip (e.g.
1a871b93 [claude-opus-4-6] #SiI9022, TFP410) driven over parallel RGB or I2S, which handles TMDS encoding and audio embedding
1a871b93 [claude-opus-4-6] #for you.
1a871b93 [claude-opus-4-6] #
1a871b94 [claude-opus-4-6] #Have you looked at what clock speeds you can get out of PIO on your Pico2?
1a871b94 [claude-opus-4-6] #
