1a8ac7cc [claude-opus-4-6] #At 150MHz, clean dividers for I2S:
1a8ac7cc [claude-opus-4-6] #
1a8ac7cc [claude-opus-4-6] #
1a8ac7cd [claude-opus-4-6] #150MHz / 50 = 3.0MHz BCK
1a8ac7cd [claude-opus-4-6] #3.0MHz / 64 = 46,875 Hz sample rate
1a8ac7cd [claude-opus-4-6] #
1a8ac7cd [claude-opus-4-6] #
1a8ac7ce [claude-opus-4-6] #Close to 48kHz but not exact. Or:
1a8ac7ce [claude-opus-4-6] #
1a8ac7ce [claude-opus-4-6] #
1a8ac7cf [claude-opus-4-6] #150MHz / 48 = 3.125MHz BCK
1a8ac7cf [claude-opus-4-6] #3.125MHz / 64 = 48,828 Hz
1a8ac7cf [claude-opus-4-6] #
1a8ac7cf [claude-opus-4-6] #
1a8ac7d0 [claude-opus-4-6] #Neither is clean. The issue is 150MHz doesn't divide evenly to standard audio rates.
1a8ac7d0 [claude-opus-4-6] #
1a8ac7d0 [claude-opus-4-6] #You could change the system clock. For exact 48kHz:
1a8ac7d0 [claude-opus-4-6] #
1a8ac7d1 [claude-opus-4-6] #
1a8ac7d1 [claude-opus-4-6] #147.456MHz / 48 = 3.072MHz BCK = exactly 48kHz
1a8ac7d1 [claude-opus-4-6] #
1a8ac7d1 [claude-opus-4-6] #
1a8ac7d2 [claude-opus-4-6] #RP2350 PLL can hit 147.456MHz. That would make your video PIO 9,216 cycles per line instead of
1a8ac7d2 [claude-opus-4-6] #9,600 - your timing constants would need adjusting but it's workable.
1a8ac7d2 [claude-opus-4-6] #
1a8ac7d2 [claude-opus-4-6] #Or keep 150MHz and accept 46,875Hz - the DAC won't care and no one will hear the difference.
1a8ac7d3 [claude-opus-4-6] #
