1a8b28a3 [nitro@ryzen5] ; i2s.pio; 16-bit stereo, 46,875 Hz; out pin = DIN (GP2); set pins = BCK (GP3), WSEL (GP4).program i2s	set	x, 15left:	set	pins, 0	out	pins, 1	set	pins, 1	jmp	x--, left	set	x, 15right:	set	pins, 2	out	pins, 1	set	pins, 3	jmp	x--, right.wrap
1a8b295b [claude-opus-4-6] #Yes that's cleaner. 16 iterations for 16 bits, the `out` inside the loop handles all of them.
1a8b295b [claude-opus-4-6] #
1a8b295b [claude-opus-4-6] #One issue: the `.wrap` jumps back to the top `set x, 15` but there's no WSEL transition between
1a8b295b [claude-opus-4-6] #right ending and left starting. The last instruction before wrap is `jmp x--, right` which falls
1a8b295c [claude-opus-4-6] #through when x wraps, then `.wrap` jumps to `set x, 15`. WSEL is still high (2) from the right
1a8b295c [claude-opus-4-6] #channel `set pins, 2/3`. It needs to go low before the first left bit.
1a8b295c [claude-opus-4-6] #
1a8b295c [claude-opus-4-6] #Your original `vidblit.pio` uses `.wrap` at the bottom only - you'd need `.wrap_target` at the `set
1a8b295d [claude-opus-4-6] #x, 15` line. And WSEL needs clearing before left starts.
1a8b295d [claude-opus-4-6] #
1a8b295d [claude-opus-4-6] #The `set x, 15` at the top already serves as that extra cycle where you could clear WSEL. So it
1a8b295d [claude-opus-4-6] #works if you add `.wrap_target` there - the flow is: right channel ends, wraps to `set x, 15`, then
1a8b295e [claude-opus-4-6] #`left:` starts with `set pins, 0` which clears WSEL. That's fine.
1a8b295e [claude-opus-4-6] #
