1a8b4baf [nitro@ryzen5] if we stuck with pure 150mhz, could we not use nops for timing?
1a8b4c5b [claude-opus-4-6] #You could, but why? The clock divider gives you exact timing with zero jitter. NOPs would waste
1a8b4c5c [claude-opus-4-6] #instruction space and you only have 32 instructions per PIO program.
1a8b4c5c [claude-opus-4-6] #
1a8b4c5c [claude-opus-4-6] #At 150MHz undivided, your 4-instruction loop gives:
1a8b4c5c [claude-opus-4-6] #
1a8b4c5d [claude-opus-4-6] #
1a8b4c5d [claude-opus-4-6] #150MHz / 4 = 37.5MHz BCK - within the 50.4MHz limit
1a8b4c5d [claude-opus-4-6] #37.5MHz / 32 = 1,171,875 Hz sample rate - way over 384kHz DAC max
1a8b4c5d [claude-opus-4-6] #
1a8b4c5e [claude-opus-4-6] #
1a8b4c5e [claude-opus-4-6] #You'd need 10 NOPs per loop iteration to get back down to 46,875 Hz. That's 14 instructions per
1a8b4c5e [claude-opus-4-6] #bit, 14 × 32 = 448 instructions per sample frame - won't fit.
1a8b4c5e [claude-opus-4-6] #
1a8b4c5f [claude-opus-4-6] #The divider is the right tool here.
1a8b4c5f [claude-opus-4-6] #
