1a9c2746 [gemini-3.1-pro] #It is functional, but there is room for optimization. Here are a few areas to consider:
1a9c2746 [gemini-3.1-pro] #
1a9c2747 [gemini-3.1-pro] #1. Redundant Bitwise Logic: Your inner loop calculates `(frame[off] & mask) | bits`.
1a9c2747 [gemini-3.1-pro] #Because `mask` is `~bits`, this perfectly simplifies to `frame[off] | bits`. Removing the mask
1a9c2747 [gemini-3.1-pro] #completely eliminates a read, a bitwise AND, and the mask generation. (Note: If you eventually want
1a9c2747 [gemini-3.1-pro] #to draw 0s instead of 1s, you will need to introduce a color parameter).
1a9c2748 [gemini-3.1-pro] #
1a9c2748 [gemini-3.1-pro] #2. Memory Access Pattern: Your loops process the rectangle in vertical columns (`off +=
1a9c2748 [gemini-3.1-pro] #22`), resulting in strided memory access. Iterating horizontally (outer loop for height, inner loop
1a9c2748 [gemini-3.1-pro] #for width) provides sequential memory access. Sequential writes are generally faster on the ARM
1a9c2749 [gemini-3.1-pro] #memory bus and allow the compiler to better optimize.
1a9c2749 [gemini-3.1-pro] #
1a9c2749 [gemini-3.1-pro] #3. Full-Word Fast Path: If you switch to a row-by-row approach, any 32-bit blocks
1a9c2749 [gemini-3.1-pro] #completely inside the rectangle (`bits == 0xffffffff`) can be written directly without needing a
1a9c274a [gemini-3.1-pro] #read-modify-write cycle. For wide rectangles, this provides a massive speed increase.
1a9c274a [gemini-3.1-pro] #
1a9c274a [gemini-3.1-pro] #Let me know if you would like to see a code example of the row-by-row approach.
