1aa3c63e [gemini-3.1-pro] #What you are seeing is analog ringing (overshoot) or cross-luma artifacts.
1aa3c63e [gemini-3.1-pro] #
1aa3c63e [gemini-3.1-pro] #Because you increased the horizontal resolution to 1536, your pixel clock is now 29.7 MHz. When you
1aa3c63f [gemini-3.1-pro] #draw a sharp vertical edge (like the side of a rectangle), the 1-bit transition from 0 to 1 happens
1aa3c63f [gemini-3.1-pro] #almost instantly.
1aa3c63f [gemini-3.1-pro] #
1aa3c640 [gemini-3.1-pro] #This creates high-frequency square-wave harmonics that extend well into the 4.43 MHz band that the
1aa3c640 [gemini-3.1-pro] #TV's PAL comb filter monitors for color. The comb filter misinterprets these sharp luma edges as
1aa3c640 [gemini-3.1-pro] #chroma information (or the TV's analog front-end simply rings trying to process the
1aa3c640 [gemini-3.1-pro] #infinite-bandwidth edge), resulting in bright borders around high-contrast transitions. At lower
1aa3c641 [gemini-3.1-pro] #resolutions, the pixels are physically wider, which changes the spatial frequency and makes the
1aa3c641 [gemini-3.1-pro] #comb filter less likely to catch them.
1aa3c641 [gemini-3.1-pro] #
1aa3c641 [gemini-3.1-pro] #Since you are using a strictly 1-bit framebuffer, you cannot anti-alias or soften the edges in
1aa3c642 [gemini-3.1-pro] #software.
1aa3c642 [gemini-3.1-pro] #
1aa3c642 [gemini-3.1-pro] #The most common fix for 1-bit microcontroller video is a hardware low-pass filter. If you add a
1aa3c642 [gemini-3.1-pro] #small capacitor (around 100pF to 220pF) between your VIDEO OUT line and GND, it forms an RC filter
1aa3c643 [gemini-3.1-pro] #with your 330Ω resistor. This gently rounds off the sharp digital edges before they reach the TV,
1aa3c643 [gemini-3.1-pro] #keeping the frequencies below the comb filter's threshold and eliminating the bright sides.
1aa3c643 [gemini-3.1-pro] #
